	Forward-Looking Statements
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	This report contains forward-looking statements within the meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#8220;Exchange Act&#8221;), and the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995 that are subject to risks and uncertainties. You should not place undue reliance on those statements because they are subject to numerous uncertainties and factors relating to our operations and business environment, all of which are difficult to predict and many of which are beyond our control. You can identify these statements by the fact that they do not relate strictly to historical or current facts. Such statements may include words such as &#8220;anticipate,&#8221; &#8220;will,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;project,&#8221; &#8220;intend,&#8221; &#8220;should,&#8221; &#8220;plan,&#8221; &#8220;believe,&#8221; &#8220;hope,&#8221; and other words and terms of similar meaning in connection with any discussion of, among other things, future operating or financial performance, strategic initiatives and business strategies, regulatory or competitive environments, our intellectual property and product development. In particular, these forward-looking statements include, among others, statements about:
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Forward-looking statements made by us in this annual report speak only as of the date of this annual report. Actual results could differ materially from those currently anticipated as a result of a number of risk factors, including, but not limited to, the risks and uncertainties discussed under the caption &#8220;Risk Factors.&#8221;&nbsp;&nbsp;New risks and uncertainties come up from time to time, and it is impossible for us to predict these events or how they may affect us. We do not undertake to update or revise the forward-looking statements in this annual report after the date of this annual report, except as required by law. In light of these risks and uncertainties, you should keep in mind that any forward-looking statement in this annual report or elsewhere might not occur.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Antares Pharma, Inc. (&#8220;Antares,&#8221; &#8220;we,&#8221; &#8220;our,&#8221; &#8220;us&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221;) is an emerging, specialty pharmaceutical company that focuses on the development and commercialization of self-administered parenteral pharmaceutical products and technologies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our subcutaneous injection technology platforms include VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	disposable pressure-assisted auto injectors, Vision
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	reusable needle-free injectors, and disposable multi-use pen injectors. We have multiple internal product development programs as well as significant partnership arrangements with several industry leading pharmaceutical companies. We have formed strategic alliances with Teva Pharmaceutical Industries, Ltd. (&#8220;Teva&#8221;), Ferring Pharmaceuticals Inc. and Ferring B.V. (together &#8220;Ferring&#8221;), JCR Pharmaceuticals Co., Ltd. (&#8220;JCR&#8221;), and AMAG Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (&#8220;AMAG&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;We develop and apply our drug delivery systems in collaborations with these pharmaceutical partners to enhance our partners' drug compounds and delivery methods.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We develop and manufacture novel, pressure-assisted injector devices, with and without needles, which allow patients to self-inject drugs.&nbsp;&nbsp;We make a reusable, needle-free spring action injection device, known as the ZOMA-Jet&#8482; or Twin-Jector
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, which is marketed through our partners for use with human growth hormone (hGH).&nbsp;&nbsp;We have developed variations of the needle-free injector by adding a small shielded needle to a pre-filled, single-use disposable injector, called the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	pressure assisted auto injection system. This system is an alternative to the needle-free system for use with injectable drugs in unit dose containers and is suitable for various branded and generic injectables.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also developed disposable multi-dose pen injectors for use with standard cartridges.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have entered into multiple licenses for these devices mainly in the U.S., Europe and Canada with Teva.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In February 2014, we launched our proprietary product OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	(methotrexate) injection, which was the first FDA-approved subcutaneous methotrexate for once weekly self-administration with an easy-to-use, single dose, disposable auto injector.&nbsp;&nbsp;OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	, which utilizes our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector, is indicated for adults with severe active rheumatoid arthritis (&#8220;RA&#8221;), children with active polyarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis (&#8220;pJIA&#8221;) and adults with severe recalcitrant psoriasis.&nbsp;&nbsp; To date, we have received FDA approval for dosage strengths of 7.5 mg, 10 mg, 15 mg, 20 mg and 25 mg of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In December 2015, the FDA approved our Abbreviated New Drug Application (ANDA) for 4 mg/0.5 mL and 6 mg/0.5 mL Sumatriptan Injection USP, indicated for adults for the acute treatment of migraine and cluster headache.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sumatriptan Injection USP represents the Company&#8217;s first ANDA approval of a complex generic and second product approved using the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector platform.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the terms of a license, supply and distribution arrangement, the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Sumatriptan product will be distributed by Teva, and is currently expected to be launched in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are collaborating with Teva on a combination product development project for a VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector pen containing epinephrine.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva submitted an amendment to the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	epinephrine pen ANDA in December 2014 and received a Complete Response Letter (&#8220;CRL&#8221;) from the FDA on February 23, 2016 in which, according to Teva, the FDA identified certain major deficiencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva is evaluating the CRL and intends to submit a response. Due to the major nature of the CRL, Teva expects that its epinephrine product will be substantially delayed from their previously anticipated launch date in the second half of 2016 and that any launch will not take place before 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage5"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU5">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	other
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	combination product development projects in collaboration with Teva include
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	exenatide multi-dose pen, and another undisclosed multi-dose pe
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	n.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Teva filed an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ANDA
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	for exenatide, which was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	accepted by the FDA
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	in October 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	and is currently under FDA review.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are currently conducting clinical studies of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T, for testosterone replacement therapy.&nbsp;&nbsp;In February 2015, we announced positive top-line pharmacokinetic results that showed that the primary endpoint was achieved in the Company&#8217;s ongoing, multi-center, phase 3 clinical study (QST-13-003) evaluating the efficacy and safety of testosterone enanthate administered once-weekly by subcutaneous injection using the QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;auto injector in testosterone deficient adult males.&nbsp;&nbsp;In October 2015, we announced that the last patient in study QST-13-003 received their week 52 treatment, which marked the end of the treatment and follow up phase of this study.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based upon a written response we received from the FDA related to our clinical development program for QS T, we are currently conducting an additional study, QST-15-005, to support the filing of our expected 505 (b) (2) New Drug Application (&#8220;NDA&#8221;) for QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;The study includes a screening phase, a treatment titration phase and a treatment phase for evaluation of safety and tolerability assessments, including laboratory assessments, adverse events and injection site assessments.&nbsp;&nbsp;We completed enrollment in study QST-15-005 in October 2015 and anticipate that the last patient in the study will complete their final visit in the second quarter of 2016. We believe we will file the NDA for QS T in late 2016 or early 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In partnership with AMAG Pharmaceuticals, Inc., we are currently developing a variation of our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector for use with AMAG&#8217;s progestin hormone drug
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
</FONT>
	Makena
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(hydroxy-progesterone caproate injection) under a license, development and supply agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under this arrangement, AMAG is responsible for the clinical development and preparation, submission and maintenance of all regulatory applications, to manufacture and supply the drug, and to market, sell and distribute the product.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are responsible for the design and development of the auto-injection device, to manufacture and supply the device, and to assemble and package the final product.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We also have two gel-based products which are commercialized through partners.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have an oxybutynin gel product, Gelnique
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	for the treatment of overactive bladder (&#8220;OAB&#8221;), which is currently marketed in the U.S. under a licensing agreement with Actavis plc (&#8220;Actavis&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Elestrin
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(estradiol gel) is currently marketed by Meda Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (&#8220;Meda&#8221;) in the U.S. for the treatment of moderate-to-severe vasomotor symptoms associated with menopause.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our products and product opportunities are summarized and briefly described below:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#160;
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	3
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage6"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU6">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Antares is a Delaware corporation with principal executive offices located at 100 Princeton South Corporate Center, Suite 300, Ewing, New Jersey 08628.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have two wholly owned subsidiaries in Switzerland (Antares Pharma AG and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Antares Pharma IPL AG).&nbsp;&nbsp;On January 31, 2001, we completed a business combination to acquire the operating subsidiaries of Permatec Holding AG, headquartered in Basel, Switzerland. Upon completion of the transaction, our name was changed from Medi Ject Cor
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	poration to Antares Pharma, Inc.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have a single reportable operating segment, drug delivery, which includes self-administered parenteral pharmaceutical products and technologies.&nbsp;&nbsp;See Note 2 to the Consolidated Financial Statements in Part II, Item 8 about segment financial information.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Market Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our focus is specifically on the market for delivery of self-administered injectable drugs, comprised of non-biologic, small molecule drugs and biological products or biosimilars.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that many injectable products currently offered in vials could be replaced with user-friendly auto injectors promoting better compliance and improvement in dose accuracy.&nbsp;&nbsp;Several manufacturers of injectable products have introduced convenient alternatives to vials, such as prefilled syringes and injector systems, and an increasing proportion of people who self-administer drugs are transitioning to prefilled syringes and other injector systems when offered. We believe that our injection technologies and products offer further improvements in convenience and comfort for patients self-administering injectable products as well as provide the appropriate technique to the patient to accurately self-inject. Additionally, the delivery of pharmaceutical therapies through injection systems often improves the systemic bioavailability of those treatments by overcoming absorption barriers common with oral and, in some cases, transdermal delivery. Improved bioavailability is considered beneficial when considering the role of route of administration on pharmaceutical efficacy. We believe our business model of developing our own pharmaceutical products in targeted therapeutic categories using our pressure-assisted auto injectors and pen injectors has the potential for further market penetration in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, partnering with pharmaceutical manufacturers of injectable products that are outside of our therapeutic focus offers us additional potential to profit from our proprietary injector systems.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	SELF-ADMINISTRATION OF INJECTABLE DRUGS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Injectable drugs are used in managing chronic medical conditions presenting a need for repeated injections over time and are also used in management of acute conditions where the rapid onset of an injected drug is desirable.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Cost containment pressure by managed care organizations, combined with patient preferences for convenience and comfort are driving a change in the treatment setting from the health care facility to patients&#8217; homes.&nbsp;&nbsp;This trend is creating a shift from the chronic care injections and even some acute care injections being administered by a doctor or nurse to self-administration by the patient, a family member, or other lay caregiver.&nbsp;&nbsp; This shift has produced a transition in how injectable drugs are configured to facilitate use by consumers.&nbsp;&nbsp;In many therapeutic categories, pre-filled syringes and other injection systems offering greater ease-of-use and security for patients now exceed vials in unit volume, often at substantial unit price premium.&nbsp;&nbsp;These therapeutic categories and example products include:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#160;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In addition to the drugs listed in the table above and the products we already have in development, we have identified other injectable single and multi-source drug products currently on the market that we believe are appropriate for self-administration and are candidates for our device technologies.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	4
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage7"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU7">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Non-biologic injectable drugs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Many non-biologic, small molecule drugs are injected rather than taken orally for one or more of several reasons, including improved absorption, onset of action, tolerability and safety. In the case of many of these compounds, bypassing the gastrointestinal tract by switching a route of administration from oral tablet to subcutaneous injection improves the side effect profile of the drug and does not cause gastrointestinal adverse events. Our OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	product is an example of changing the route of administration from oral to injection for better bioavailability, systemic absorption, and tolerability. VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Sumatriptan and VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Epinephrine are examples of using the injection route for faster onset of action that is thought to result in more-rapid symptomatic relief. Generic products, like sumatriptan and methotrexate, represent a large portion of non-biologic injectable product volume in the current market.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	THERAPEUTIC PRODUCTS AND PRODUCT MARKET OPPORTUNITIES FOR OUR INJECTOR SYSTEMS
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	(methotrexate) injection
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	is our proprietary combination product comprised of a pre-filled methotrexate syringe and our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	self-injection system designed to enable rheumatoid arthritis and psoriasis patients to self-inject methotrexate reliably, accurately, comfortably and conveniently at home. On October 14, 2013, we announced the FDA had approved OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	(methotrexate) injection, the first FDA-approved subcutaneous methotrexate for once weekly self-administration with an easy-to-use, single dose, disposable auto injector.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our new drug application (&#8220;NDA&#8221;) approved in October 2013 covered the 10 mg, 15 mg, 20 mg and 25 mg dosage strengths.&nbsp;&nbsp;In July 2014, we submitted a supplemental NDA for the 7.5 mg strength of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	, and we received FDA approval in November 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	is indicated for use in adults with severe, active RA or children with active polyarticular juvenile arthritis (&#8220;pJIA&#8221;) who are intolerant of or had an inadequate response to first&#8209;line therapy, including full dose non&#8209;steroidal anti&#8209;inflammatory agents, and adults with severe recalcitrant psoriasis.&nbsp;&nbsp;RA is a chronic autoimmune disease, resulting in pain, stiffness, swelling, joint damage, and loss of function of the joints. According to the Arthritis Foundation, RA affects approximately 1.5 million Americans, which is almost 0.5% of the U.S. population.&nbsp;&nbsp;The disease onset generally occurs between the ages of 30 to 60 years in women.&nbsp;&nbsp;In men, it often occurs later in life.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to Symphony Health Solutions, a healthcare data and analytics company, U.S. sales of biologic drug products approved to treat rheumatoid arthritis were approximately $20.0 billion in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Some of these agents are also approved for other indications including plaque psoriasis, Crohn&#8217;s disease, ulcerative colitis, juvenile idiopathic, ankylosing spondylitis, and psoriatic arthritis, making it difficult to determine the proportion of sales attributable to use in rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Methotrexate is the most commonly prescribed disease modifying anti-rheumatic drug (&#8220;DMARD&#8221;), used in an estimated 70% of rheumatoid arthritis patients.&nbsp;&nbsp;A November 2012 analysis utilizing United Healthcare data and&nbsp;&nbsp;conducted by Optum found that methotrexate is usually started at 7.5 mg, 10 mg or 15 mg given orally, once-a-week, and titrated up for greater therapeutic effect, or until the patient incurs side effects.&nbsp;&nbsp;The maximum oral dose given is generally 20 mg to 25 mg per week (8 to 10, 2.5 mg tablets given in one dose).&nbsp;&nbsp;Studies have reported as many as 30% to 60% of patients experience gastrointestinal side effects with oral methotrexate, preventing further dose escalation or requiring discontinuation in some patients.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, the extent of oral absorption of methotrexate varies considerably between patients. In a study performed by Schiff et al published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The Annals of Rheumatic Diseases
</FONT>
	in 2014, researchers showed that the bioavailability of methotrexate delivered via subcutaneous injection was dose proportional and continued to increase compared with oral drug, which plateaued at 15 mg.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to studies by Dr. Wegrzyn published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The Annals of Rheumatic Diseases
</FONT>
	in 2004, Dr. Mainman published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Rheumatology
</FONT>
	in 2010, Dr. Bakker published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The Annals of Rheumatic Diseases
</FONT>
	in 2010, and Dr. Braun published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Arthritis and Rheumatism
</FONT>
	in 2008, RA patients switching from oral to parenteral methotrexate may improve clinical response or lower the incidence of gastrointestinal side effects.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Other rheumatological conditions for which methotrexate is an approved treatment are pJIA in children who have had an insufficient therapeutic response to, or are intolerant of, an adequate trial of first-line therapy including full dose non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agents (&#8220;NSAIDs&#8221;) and in patients with severe, recalcitrant, disabling psoriasis that is not adequately responsive to other forms of therapy after a definite diagnosis has been established.&nbsp;&nbsp;As indicated in the OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	prescribing information, the recommended dosing schedule for methotrexate in psoriasis is 10 to 25 mg per week until adequate response is achieved.&nbsp;&nbsp;In pJIA the recommended starting dose is 10 mg/m
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	2
</SUP>
	given once weekly.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Psoriasis is believed to be an autoimmune disease, characterized by thick patches of inflamed, scaly skin, created by abnormal, rapid, and excessive proliferation of skin cells.&nbsp;&nbsp;The National Psoriasis Foundation, a non-profit health agency dedicated to curing psoriatic disease, stated in 2015 that psoriasis is the most prevalent autoimmune disease in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to current studies, as many as 7.5 million Americans, or approximately 2.2% of the population suffer from psoriasis, with a higher incidence in Caucasians.&nbsp;&nbsp;And, according to information published by the World Psoriasis Day consortium in 2015, 125 million people worldwide, or 2% to 3% of the total population have psoriasis.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	5
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage8"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU8">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	pJIA is the most common rheumatic disease in childhood with an est
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	imated prevalence between 7 and 400 for every 100,000 children.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to the Arthritis Foundation, pJIA affects nearly 300,000 children in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;Most forms of pJIA are autoimmune disorders that cause pain, swelling, stiffness, and loss of motion i
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	n the joints.&nbsp;&nbsp;It can persist over many years and can also lead to disability and dysfunction in adulthood.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	offers physicians and patients an important alternative to oral methotrexate tablets and vials of the injectable form of the drug administered with a needle and syringe.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to studies by Dr. Wegrzyn published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The Annals of Rheumatic Diseases
</FONT>
	in 2004, Dr. Mainman published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Clinical Rheumatology
</FONT>
	in 2010, Dr. Bakker published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The Annals of Rheumatic Diseases
</FONT>
	in 2010, and Dr. Braun published in
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Arthritis and Rheumatism
</FONT>
	in 2008, many patients who start on oral methotrexate may have an inadequate clinical response due in part to a lack of efficacy or poor tolerability. Although published studies have demonstrated switching to a parenteral route of administration can improve absorption, a 2015 report by Symphony Healthcare found that approximately 7% of patients on methotrexate are being prescribed the injectable form.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Instead, patients who fail to achieve adequate response on oral methotrexate are often prescribed a biologic response modifier (&#8220;biologic&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Biologic therapies have been demonstrated to improve the patient&#8217;s therapeutic response when added to methotrexate.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, according to Source Healthcare Analytics data published in 2013, the average retail price for biologics was in excess of $32,000 annually, excluding administrative and other fees that could be incurred.&nbsp;&nbsp;A number of peer-reviewed articles by key thought leaders in the rheumatology community have called on clinicians to optimize methotrexate therapy for rheumatoid arthritis and ensure that the drug is given adequate time to achieve the desired results before biologic therapies are initiated.&nbsp;&nbsp;Biologics have shown to have their own limitations including increasing the risk of serious infections and certain malignancies and are not appropriate for all patients.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In a phase 2 clinical study by Freundlich, et al, in 2014, OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	was well tolerated with almost no administration site pain and minimal erythema. Limitations in functional status did not affect ability to self-administer. Improving the delivery of subcutaneous methotrexate may increase patient tolerance of self-injection thereby improving adherence in patients with RA.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	may offer physicians and patients a convenient, practical and cost-effective option for administering parenteral methotrexate as an alternative to proceeding directly from oral methotrexate to biologics.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	is a self-contained injection device designed to minimize accidental contact with methotrexate, a hazardous drug agent.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Since its launch in February 2014, OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	has been prescribed by nearly 2,000 physicians. The Company&#8217;s marketing data reveal that some physicians regularly use OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	in RA patients who have experienced an inadequate response to oral methotrexate therapy for reasons of tolerability and/or efficacy.&nbsp;&nbsp; We have worldwide marketing rights for OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	and independently market OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	on our own in the U.S. for the treatment of RA.&nbsp;&nbsp;Commercial sales of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	commenced in early 2014, with good initial clinical adoption/utilization, and reimbursement status among payer organizations that is consistent with other in-class products.&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2014, Medac Pharma Inc. (&#8220;Medac Pharma&#8221;), a privately held pharmaceutical company, announced FDA approval of an NDA for their product, Rasuvo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	, a subcutaneous injectable methotrexate in a ready-to-use injection device indicated for the treatment of management of adults with severe, active RA or children with active pJIA who are intolerant of or had an inadequate response to first&#8209;line therapy, including full dose non&#8209;steroidal anti&#8209;inflammatory agents. Medac Pharma launched Rasuvo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	on October 6, 2014. The product is available in 10 dosage strengths, ranging from 7.5 mg to 30 mg in 2.5 mg increments.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	QS T (testosterone)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Testosterone (&#8220;QS T&#8221;) is our proprietary combination product that consists of testosterone and our next generation VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(&#8220;QS&#8221;) auto injector in development for the treatment of testosterone deficiency or testosterone replacement therapy.&nbsp;&nbsp; The VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS auto injector is designed specifically to provide a fast injection of highly viscous fluids such as testosterone in oil.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The U.S. testosterone replacement therapy (&#8220;TRT&#8221;) market in 2015 was approximately $2.8 billion according to a Symphony Health Solutions report.&nbsp;&nbsp;Injectable TRT grew from $212.0 million in 2013 to $237.0 million in 2015, an increase of almost 12%. &nbsp;&nbsp;There is significant competition within the TRT market among many pharmaceutical companies including Abbvie, Inc. (formerly Abbott), Eli Lilly and Company (&#8220;Lilly&#8221;), Endo Pharmaceuticals, Inc (&#8220;Endo&#8221;), Pfizer, Inc. (&#8220;Pfizer&#8221;), Actavis PLC (&#8220;Actavis&#8221;), Sandoz, Inc. (&#8220;Sandoz&#8221;), Mylan, Inc. (&#8220;Mylan&#8221;), Bedford Laboratories (&#8220;Bedford&#8221;), and Teva.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU9">
</A>
	According to the Urology Care Foundation in June 2014, low serum testosterone, also known as hypogonadism or andropause, affects roughly four out of 10 men over the age of 45. The prevalence of low testosterone increases with age.&nbsp;&nbsp;Researchers have found that the incidence of low testosterone increases from approximately 20% of men over 60, to 30% of men over 70 and 30% of men over 80 years of age.&nbsp;&nbsp;In May 2014, Forbes.com estimated 13 million men in the U.S. suffer from lower than average testosterone.&nbsp;&nbsp;Symptoms and health risks associated with low testosterone include compromised sexual function, loss of bone density, reduced muscle mass, lethargy, mood disorders, impaired cognition, and cardiovascular disease.&nbsp;&nbsp;Several factors, including low awareness,
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	6
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage9"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	embarrassment and stigma associated with low testosterone are believed to contribute to the relatively low diagnosis and treatment levels.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Testosterone re
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	placement therapy is given to restore patients&#8217; testosterone levels to within the normal range,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	t
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	he potential benefits of therapy include
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	improved sexual
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	function, increased energy levels, and improved mood. TRT can also improve body composition by decreasing fat mass, increase lean body mass, potentially increase muscle strength, and stabilize or increase bone mineral density, as well as reduce bone fract
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Topical formulations of TRT, such as Androgel, Testim, Fortesta, Axiron, dermal patches and buccal delivery are frequently prescribed versions of TRT.&nbsp;&nbsp;Not all men are able to adequately absorb the gel formulations or otherwise find them unacceptable for reasons including risks of transferring the gel to spouses or children, dissatisfaction with the application process, or suboptimal clinical results due to variability in exposure and compliance.&nbsp;&nbsp;Injectable testosterone is an option for men with an inadequate response to transdermal therapies. Additionally, there are three oral formulations currently under various stages of development to treat testosterone deficiency.&#160; The companies developing these products are Repros Therapeutics, Clarus Therapeutics and Lipocine.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Currently, injectable testosterone is available and represents a significant percentage of all TRT prescriptions. These injections, prescribed as a combination of a vial, needle, and syringe, are usually given deep into the muscle tissue of the buttocks with large bore needles (typically 19 gauge needles).&nbsp;&nbsp;Injection testosterone is an esterified formulation in oil that is absorbed slowly from the muscle tissue, producing a sustained increase in serum testosterone over time, requiring repeated injections typically administered in the physician&#8217;s office every two to four weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;The higher doses given to facilitate less frequent injections are sometimes associated with supra-physiologic levels.&nbsp;&nbsp;Such high levels may lead to polycythemia, a proliferation of red blood cells, which places the patient at increased risk of thrombus or clot formation leading to strokes, heart attacks, pulmonary embolism, and possibly death.&nbsp;&nbsp; Excessive variability between peak testosterone levels occurring shortly after the injection to the lowest levels immediately preceding a dose are also associated with mood swings.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	For these reasons, we are developing VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T, a once-weekly subcutaneous injectable testosterone product that could be conveniently self-administered at potentially lower dosages given more frequently than is generally practical with repeated visits to the physician&#8217;s office.&nbsp;&nbsp;The VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T utilizes a small gauge needle for patient comfort.&nbsp;&nbsp;See
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Research and Development
</FONT>
	below and Part II Item 7 Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations for a discussion of research and development for VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	(hGH)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ZOMA-Jet&#8482; is our needle-free auto injector offered by Ferring to patients who use its brand of hGH.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is designed to deliver hGH treatment to children without the use of a needle.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	According to Symphony Health Solutions, hGH sales in the U.S. were $1.8 billion in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;There is significant competition within the hGH market between major pharmaceutical companies such as F. Hoffmann-La Roche AG, Pfizer, Novo Nordisk, Inc, Sandoz, and EMD Serono, Inc. among others.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that product attributes, including patient comfort and ease-of-use, play a key role, along with price and promotion, in determining performance in the market.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	device can administer injectables by using a spring to push the active ingredient in solution or suspension through a micro-fine opening in the needle-free syringe. The opening is approximately half the diameter of a standard 30-gauge needle. A fine liquid stream then penetrates the skin, and the dose is dispersed into the layer of fatty, subcutaneous tissue. The drug is subsequently distributed throughout the body, successfully producing the desired effect.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe this method of administration is a particularly attractive alternative to the needle and syringe for the groups of patients described below:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:9.06%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Patient Candidates for Needle-Free Injection
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	7

<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage10"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU10">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ZOMA-Jet
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	device is primarily used in the U.S., Europe, Asia, Japan
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	and elsewhere to provide a needle-free means of administering human growth hormone to patients with growth retardation. We typically sell our injection devices to partners in these markets who manufacture and/or market human growth hormone directly. The p
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	artners then market our device with their growth hormone. We receive benefits from these agreements in the form of product sales and royalties on sales of their products.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	device has been sold for use in more than 30 countries to deliver hGH. The product is reusable, with each device designed to last for approximately 3,000 injections (or approximately two years) while the needle-free syringe is disposable after approximately one week when used by a patient for injecting from multi-dose vials. Our pharmaceutical partner, JCR, markets hGH in Japan as the Twin-Jector
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	EZ II Needle-free Injector.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our pharmaceutical partner, Ferring, has an established branded product in the hGH market using our needle-free injector, marketed as the ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	2 Vision for their 4 mg formulation and ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	Vision X for their 10 mg formulation.&nbsp;&nbsp;In December 2014, Ferring acquired the U.S. rights to Tev-Tropin
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	from Teva and assumed Teva&#8217;s obligations under the device supply agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March 31, 2015, we announced that Ferring had received FDA approval of a name change to ZOMACTON (somatropin [rDNA origin] for injection, and the needle free delivery system to be marketed in the U.S. as ZOMA-Jet
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ferring also received approval from the FDA to market the 10 mg needle free injection device which, along with the consumables, is supplied by Antares to Ferring.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	with Epinephrine
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have a license, development and supply agreement with Teva for our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system which we have designed for a product containing epinephrine.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have scaled-up the commercial tooling and molds for this product, and have shipped pre-launch quantities of devices to Teva.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are awaiting FDA approval of the product as a generic substitute of Mylan&#8217;s branded product, EpiPen
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	. Teva submitted an amendment to the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	epinephrine pen ANDA in December 2014 and received a CRL from the FDA on February 23, 2016 in which, according to Teva, the FDA identified certain major deficiencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva is evaluating the CRL and intends to submit a response. Due to the major nature of the CRL, Teva expects that its epinephrine product will be substantially delayed from the previously anticipated launch date in the second half of 2016 and that any launch will not take place before 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The EpiPen
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	is the global market leader in the epinephrine auto injector market.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the U.S., according to Symphony Health Solutions, sales of epinephrine injection products were approximately $2.2 billion in 2015 with the EpiPen
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	accounting for 87% of the total.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Mylan, Inc. reported that EpiPen
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	has a 90% world market share in the U.S. and worldwide.&nbsp;&nbsp;Epinephrine is utilized for the treatment of severe allergic reactions (anaphylaxis) to insect venom, foods, drugs and other allergens as well as anaphylaxis to unknown substances or exercise-induced anaphylaxis.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	with Sumatriptan
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In December 2015, we received FDA approval of our ANDA for 4 mg/0.5 mL and 6 mg/0.5 mL Sumatriptan Injection USP for the acute treatment of migraine and cluster headache in adults. The reference listed drug in the ANDA was GlaxoSmithKline&#8217;s Imitrex
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Injection.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have a license, supply and distribution agreement with Teva for our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system, under which Teva will supply the drug and commercialize and distribute the finished product.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are currently preparing for commercialization of the product.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to Symphony Health Solutions, the total U.S. retail anti-migraine market was $5.6 billion in 2015. Oral drugs accounted for $4.8 billion of the total, and injectable products accounted for approximately $200 million of the total market.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	There are currently seven triptans marketed in the U.S. indicated for treatment of migraine.&nbsp;&nbsp;Five are available as generics and two retain patent exclusivity.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to Catamaran, patent protection for Eletriptan (Relpax, Pfizer) will expire in December 2016, while patent protection for Almotriptan (Axert, Janssen) ends in June 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	According to a survey commissioned by the National Headache Foundation, migraine affects nearly 37 million Americans.&nbsp;&nbsp;Migraine headaches are often characterized by a headache of moderate or severe intensity, nausea (the most common characteristic), one-sided and/or pulsating quality, aggravated by routine physical activity, duration of hours to 2-3 days; and an attack frequency anywhere between once a year and once a week.&nbsp;&nbsp;Healthcare professionals frequently prescribe triptans to stop migraine attacks , such as GSK&#8217;s Imitrex (sumatriptan) and Amerge (naratriptan); Pfizer&#8217;s Relpax (eletriptan), Merck &amp; Co., Inc.&#8217;s (&#8220;Merck&#8221;) Maxalt (rizatriptan), Impax Laboratories&#8217; Zomig (zolmitriptan), Janssen Pharmaceuticals&#8217; Axert (almotriptan),&nbsp;&nbsp;and Endo Pharmaceuticals&#8217; Frova (frovatriptan) to relieve acute symptoms of a migraine attack (Medco claims database study).
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The majority of patients who use triptans take oral tablets.&nbsp;&nbsp;While oral triptans have benefited many migraine sufferers, they are most consistently effective when taken at a relatively early stage in the migraine attack. None is as effective &#8211; and as rapid-acting as injectable sumatriptan in treating a migraine headache that has reached the moderate to severe level of intensity.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	About 14% of triptan prescriptions are currently for injectable triptans.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sumatriptan is the only injectable triptan approved for use in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sumatriptan is currently available in an oral formation, a nasal spray (Imitrex, GSK and generic), a needless injector (Sumavel, Astellas/Zogenix), and a transdermal patch (Zecuity, Teva).
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	8
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage11"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU11">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Several manufacturers offer versions of injectable sumatriptan with a delivery device,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	including GSK (Imitrex StatDose), Pfizer (Alsuma)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	, ENDO Pharmaceuticals
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	(Sumavel DosePro), and Sun Pharma (generic sumatriptan autoinjector) and Dr. Reddy&#8217;s Laboratories
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	generic sumatriptan auto-injector
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	(
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Zembrace SymTouch
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	).&nbsp;&nbsp;Two companies, Par Pharmaceuti
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	cal Companies, Inc. and Sandoz, market authorized generic versions of GSK&#8217;s Imitrex STATdose.&nbsp;&nbsp;At least three companies, including Bedford Labs, Teva, and Fresenius Kabi have FDA approval to market injection sumatriptan in prefilled syringes, although we a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	re not aware of any that presently market this product configuration.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, several generics manufacturers offer injectable sumatriptan in vials.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	(hydroxyprogesterone caproate injection)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have a development and license agreement with AMAG Pharmaceuticals, Inc. to develop and supply a subcutaneous auto injector system for use with its progestin drug Makena
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(hydroxyprogesterone caproate) indicated for the prevention of preterm birth in women who are pregnant with one baby and who have delivered one baby too early in the past.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently, Makena
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	is administered by a healthcare provider intramuscularly through a 21 gauge needle.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Disposable Pen Injector with Exenatide
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our multi use, disposable pen injector complements our portfolio of single-use pressure assisted auto injector devices.&nbsp;&nbsp;The disposable pen injector device is designed to deliver drugs by injection through needles from multi-dose cartridges.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our disposable pen injector is designed for chronic conditions such as diabetes, which require daily injection of a product.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending on dose, our pens can hold up to thirty days of drug dosing.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are planning to scale up tooling and molds for commercial scale production.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although differing from the other pressure assisted injection strategies common to the above portfolio of injection therapy, this device includes a dosing mechanism design that is drawn from our variable dose needle-free technology.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have signed a license agreement for an exenatide pen injector with Teva, which has an ANDA under active review at the FDA.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Exenatide, marketed as Byetta, is used along with diet and exercise to treat type 2 diabetes, a condition in which the body does not use insulin normally and therefore cannot control the amount of sugar in the blood. &#160;Exenatide works by stimulating the pancreas to secrete insulin when blood sugar levels are high. Insulin helps move sugar from the blood into other body tissues where it is used for energy. Exenatide also slows the emptying of the stomach and causes a decrease in appetite. Exenatide is not used to treat type 1 diabetes, a condition in which the body does not produce insulin and therefore cannot control the amount of sugar in the blood. &#160;Exenatide is not used instead of insulin to treat people with diabetes who need insulin.&#160; Total U.S. sales of Exenatide/Byetta by Astrazeneca AB (&#8220;Astrazeneca&#8221;) and Amylin Pharmaceuticals, LLC (&#8220;Amylin&#8221;)&#160;in 2015 were approximately $350 million according to Symphony Health Solutions. Bydureon, a long acting form of the medication Byetta, had approximately $822 million in U.S. sales in 2015, according to Symphony Health Solutions.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Other Injectable Drugs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Other injectable drugs that are presently self-administered and may be suitable for injection with our systems include therapies for the treatment of gout, epileptic seizure, Alzheimer&#8217;s Disease, blood clots, multiple sclerosis, inflammatory diseases, impotence, infertility, AIDS and hepatitis.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that many injectable drugs currently under development will be administered by self-injection once they reach the market. Our belief is supported by the continuing development of important chronic care products that can only be given by injection, the ongoing effort to reduce hospital and institutional costs by early patient release, and the gathering momentum of new classes of drugs that require injection.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A partial list of such drugs (and their manufacturer) introduced in recent years that require self-injection include Cimzia
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(UCB), Simponi
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Centocor Ortho Biotech), Enbrel
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Amgen, Pfizer) and Humira
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Abbvie) for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis, Epogen
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	and Aranesp
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Amgen) for treatment of anemia, Forteo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	(Lilly) for treatment of osteoporosis, Intron
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	A (Merck) and Roferon
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Roche) for hepatitis C, Lantus
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Sanofi Aventis) and Byetta
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(Bristol Myers)&nbsp;&nbsp;for diabetes, Rebif
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">

<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;

</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Technology and Product Platforms
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are leveraging our experience in device technologies to enhance the product performance of established drugs as well as new drugs in development. Our current portfolio includes disposable pressure assisted auto injection systems (VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), disposable pen injection systems and reusable needle-free injection systems.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	9
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage12"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU12">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Disposable (
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN BOLD;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	) Injectors
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A significant challenge beyond discovery of new molecules is how to effectively deliver them by means other than conventional needle and syringe. The majority of these molecules have not, to date, been amenable to oral administration due to a combination of several factors, including breakdown in the gastrointestinal tract, fundamentally poor absorption, or high first pass liver metabolism.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Pressure assisted auto injection is a form of parenteral drug delivery that continues to gain acceptance among the medical and patient community. Encompassing a wide variety of sizes and designs, this technology operates by using pressure to force the drug, in solution or suspension, through the skin and deposits the drug into the subcutaneous tissue. We have designed disposable, pressure assisted auto injector devices to address acute and chronic medical needs, such as rheumatoid arthritis and psoriasis, allergic reactions, migraine headaches, acute pain and other undisclosed therapies.&nbsp;&nbsp; Our proprietary VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	disposable auto injector systems combine a spring-based power source with a shielded needle, which delivers the needed drug solution subcutaneously or intramuscularly.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In order to minimize the anxiety and perceived pain associated with injection-based technologies, the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system features a triggering collar that shields the needle from view. The patented retracting collar springs back and locks in place as a protective needle guard after the injection, making the device safe for general disposal. In clinical studies, this device has outperformed other delivery methods in terms of completeness of injection and user preference, while limiting pain and bleeding. A summary of the key competitive advantages of the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system is provided below:
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:9.06%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Competitive Advantages of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Disposable Injectors
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
