	&#183;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
	Designed around conventional pre-filled syringes
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The primary goal of the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	disposable pressure assisted auto injector is to provide a fast, safe, and time-efficient method of self-injection. This device is designed around conventional single dose pre-filled syringes, which is a primary drug container, offering ease of transition for potential pharmaceutical partners.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have signed two license agreements with Teva for our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of these agreements is for a product containing epinephrine and the other is for sumatriptan.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also developed the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector system for delivery of methotrexate (OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	) for treatment of RA, pJIA and psoriasis.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our latest advancement in our proprietary line of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injectors is the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS auto injector system which offers a dose capacity of 1 mL and greater in a compact design. VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS is designed to enhance performance on the attributes most critical to patient acceptance&#8212;speed, comfort and discretion.&nbsp;&nbsp;VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS achieves these advancements by incorporating a novel triggering mechanism and space-saving spring configuration. The new design also accommodates fast injection of highly viscous drug products that stall less-powerful conventional auto injectors.&nbsp;&nbsp;Many self-injectable biological agents currently marketed and in clinical development are formulated to be administered in a 1 mL dose volume and tend to be of higher viscosity than non-biologic injectable products. &nbsp;&nbsp;We are developing products based on the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS system, including the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T for delivery of testosterone as replacement therapy in men who have testosterone deficiency, VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS M with an undisclosed drug for treatment of a CNS indication, and VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS for use with the progestin hormone drug Makena
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	used to lower the risk of preterm birth.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Disposable Pen Injector System
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our multi-use, disposable pen injector complements our portfolio of single-use pressure assisted auto injector devices.&nbsp;&nbsp;The disposable pen injector device is designed to deliver drugs by injection through needles from multi-dose cartridges.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our disposable pen injector is designed for chronic conditions such as diabetes, which require daily injection of a product.&nbsp;&nbsp;Depending on dose, our pens can hold up to thirty days of drug dosing.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have begun to scale up tooling and molds for potential commercial scale production.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although differing from the other pressure assisted injection strategies common to the above portfolio of injection therapy, this device includes a dosing mechanism design that is drawn from our variable dose needle-free technology.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have signed a license agreement with Teva for our pen injector device for two products: an undisclosed pen device under development for use in U.S. and Europe, and an exenatide pen which has an ANDA under active review at the FDA.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	10
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage13"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU13">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Needle-Free Injectors
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Needle-free injection combines proven delivery technology for molecules that require parenteral administration with a device that eliminates the part of the injection that patients dislike &#8211; the needle.&nbsp;&nbsp;Improving patient comfort through needle-free injection may increase compliance and mitigate the problem of daily injections. Needle-free delivery eliminates the risk of needlestick injuries as well, which occur frequently in institutions in the U.S., and can result in disease transmission to healthcare workers. One of the primary factors influencing development in the category of needle-free injection is the inherent problematic dependence on needles. It is also recognized that greater willingness to accept injection therapy could have a beneficial impact on disease outcomes.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, needle-free devices may be commercially limited due to the high cost of the product and the need for consumable disposables.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Research and Development
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;LETTER-SPACING:0.1PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We conduct clinical, regulatory, formulation development, parenteral device development and commercial development activities for internal and partnered products.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have several products at various stages of development as highlighted in our &#8220;Products and Product Opportunities&#8221; schedule in the Overview section above.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, see Collaborative Arrangements and License Agreements in this Item 1 for a discussion of pharmaceutical partners that are developing compounds using our technology.&nbsp;&nbsp;For a discussion of amounts we have spent on research and development activities, see Research and Development in Item 7 &#8211; Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations. The following is a discussion of our significant research and development programs.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T (testosterone)
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are developing VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T for self-administered weekly injections of testosterone enanthate in a preservative free formulation for clinically testosterone deficient men requiring testosterone replacement therapy.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On December 5, 2012, we conducted a pre-IND (Investigational New Drug application) meeting with the FDA as part of preparing to initiate clinical development of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T, establishing an agreed upon clinical path forward.&nbsp;&nbsp;In September 2013, we announced that the first patients were dosed in a clinical study evaluating the PK profile of testosterone enanthate administered weekly by subcutaneous injection at doses of 50 mg and 100 mg via the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T auto injector device in testosterone deficient adult males. The study enrolled 39 patients at nine investigative sites in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;We announced our top line results of this study in a press release on February 20, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that the results are positive in that VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T treatment resulted in most patients achieving average levels of testosterone within the normal range from the first dose onward.&nbsp;&nbsp;VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T was also safe and well tolerated by all dosed patients.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On November 3, 2014, we announced that the last patient had been enrolled in a double-blind, multiple-dose, phase III study (QST-13-003) to evaluate the efficacy and safety of&nbsp;&nbsp;VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T administered subcutaneously once each week to testosterone-deficient adult males.&nbsp;&nbsp;Patients enrolled in this study had a documented diagnosis of hypogonadism or testosterone deficiency defined as having testosterone levels below 300 ng/dL.&nbsp;&nbsp;The study includes a screening phase, a treatment titration and efficacy phase and an extended treatment phase.&nbsp;&nbsp;One hundred fifty patients were enrolled in this study.&nbsp;&nbsp;Patients meeting all eligibility criteria were assigned to receive a starting dose of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T once weekly for six weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;Adjustments to dose could be made at week seven based upon the week six pre-dose blood level.&nbsp;&nbsp;The efficacy of VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS T and dose adjustment to regulate testosterone levels were evaluated after 12 weeks of treatment.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	On February 25, 2015, we announced positive top-line pharmacokinetic results that showed that the primary endpoint was achieved in QST-13-003.&nbsp;&nbsp; The protocol for the study required that at the week 12 endpoint: (i) at least 75% of all patients&#8217; C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	avg
</SUB>
	are within the normal range of 300 to 1100 ng/dL, with a lower limit of a 95% 2-sided confidence interval of greater than or equal to 65%, (ii) at least 85% of patients&#8217; C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	max
</SUB>
	are less than1500 ng/dL and (iii) no more than 5% of patients had a C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	max
</SUB>
	greater than 1800 ng/dL. The primary endpoint of the population that received one or more doses of QS T was met by 139 out of 150 patients, equating to 92.7% with a 95% confidence interval of 87.3% to 96.3%.&nbsp;&nbsp;Among the 137 patients that completed all 12 weeks of dosing and PK sampling, 98.5% were within the pre-defined range.&nbsp;&nbsp;The top-line results are summarized in the table below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&#160;
</P>

</DIV>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:4.54%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	*
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	All patients with 1 or more doses, C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	avg
</SUB>
	0-168 hours post week 12 injection or last measured concentration carried forward
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:4.54%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	**
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	Patients without a C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	max
</SUB>
	determination at week 12 are assigned above 1500 ng/dL
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	11
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage14"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU14">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overall, the regimen demonstrated a mean (&#177; standard deviation) steady state concentration of testosterone of 553.3 &#177; 127.3 ng/dL at 12 weeks.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Participants in the study remained on QS T and were followed for an additional 40 weeks for the collection of safety data.&nbsp;&nbsp; One hundred fifty patients have received at least one dose of study drug.&nbsp;&nbsp;To date, there has been one reported death, which was caused by suicide, and the Company cannot rule out the role of the study drug. There was one serious adverse event (&#8220;SAE&#8221;) of hospitalization for worsening depression in a patient with a history of depression.&nbsp;&nbsp;This patient received a single dose of QS T, and the investigator concluded that the SAE was not considered to be related to the study drug.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has concluded that the single dose exposure makes it unlikely that the SAE was related to the study drug and more likely to be due to the patient&#8217;s history of depression and recent discontinuance of antidepressants.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	After we initiated study QST-13-003, but before we announced positive top-line pharmacokinetic results in February 2015, we received written recommendations from the FDA related to our clinical development program for QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;The recommendations received were in response to various clinical, Chemistry, Manufacturing and Controls and user study submissions that we made through November 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that we had already factored many of the recommendations cited in the advice letter into the protocol of the ongoing QST-13-003 study and into the protocols for planned human use studies as a result of guidance provided by the FDA at the May 2014 Type C meeting.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on a single reported occurrence of hives in our phase II study, the FDA recommended that we create a larger safety database, including approximately 350 subjects exposed to QS T with approximately 200 subjects exposed for six months and approximately 100 subjects exposed for a year.&nbsp;&nbsp;We assessed the FDA&#8217;s comments in the advice letter and their impact on the timing of the filing of a New Drug Application (&#8220;NDA&#8221;) for QS T with the FDA.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on the number of subjects in previous studies and in the current QST-13-003 study, we concluded that we would need additional subjects exposed to QS T for six months.&nbsp;&nbsp;The timing and design of the study to obtain the additional subjects and data required was determined based on further discussion with the FDA.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We submitted our response to the FDA&#8217;s written recommendations in early March 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In May 2015, we received a written update from the FDA related to our clinical development program for QS T. We believe, based on the update received from the FDA, there is an agreed upon path forward for the completion of an additional study to support the filing of a New Drug Application for QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;In June 2015, we finalized and submitted the protocol for the study, and in August 2015, we enrolled the first patients in the study, which is known as QST-15-005. The study includes a screening phase, a treatment titration phase and a treatment phase for evaluation of safety and tolerability assessments, including laboratory assessments, adverse events and injection site assessments.&nbsp;&nbsp;The study is a dose-blind, multiple-dose, concentration controlled 26-week supplemental safety and pharmacokinetic study of QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Testosterone.&nbsp;&nbsp;Patients meeting all eligibility criteria will be assigned to receive 75 mg of QS T once weekly for six weeks.&nbsp;&nbsp;According to the protocol, adjustments to dose may be made at week seven based upon the week six C
<SUB STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:BOTTOM">
	trough
</SUB>
	value.&nbsp;&nbsp;QS T will be provided to clinical sites at dosage strengths of 100 mg, 75 mg and 50 mg to be utilized in dose titration.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In October 2015, we announced that the last patient in study QST-13-003 received their week 52 treatment, which marked the end of the treatment phase of this study.&nbsp;&nbsp;In early November 2015, the Company also announced that enrollment was complete in study QST-15-005. At that time, 108 patients had received a dose of QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;Following completion of screening, 133 patients were dosed with QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company believes that upon successful completion of this study we should be able to meet or exceed the FDA&#8217;s recommendation for the larger safety database as discussed above.&nbsp;&nbsp;We anticipate the last patient in the study will complete their final visit in the second quarter of 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In addition to the clinical trial program, there is an ongoing Human Factors program to demonstrate safe and reliable at-home usability of QS T.&nbsp;&nbsp;Study populations include trained and untrained subjects, including patients, non-patient caregivers and health care providers.&nbsp;&nbsp;The goals of the program are to optimize and document reliable and proper administration in study subjects in the setting of at-home use in order to support the approvability of the product.
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:36PT;">
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Device Development Projects.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;We, along with our pharmaceutical partners, are engaged in research and development activities related to our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	disposable pressure assisted auto injectors, our QS auto injectors, and our disposable pen injectors.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have signed license agreements with Teva for our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	system for a product containing epinephrine and for a product containing sumatriptan as well as for our pen injector devices for a product containing exenatide and for an undisclosed product. We also have a license, development and supply agreement with AMAG for our QS device containing Makena
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	indicated for reduced risk of preterm birth. Our pressure assisted auto injectors are designed to deliver drugs by injection from single dose prefilled syringes.&nbsp;&nbsp;The disposable pen injector device is designed to deliver drugs by injection through needles from multi-dose cartridges.&nbsp;&nbsp;The development programs consist of determination of the device design, development of prototype tooling, production of prototype devices for testing and clinical studies, and development of commercial tooling and assembly.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following is a summary of the development stage for the four products in development with Teva and the development stage of our product with AMAG.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	12
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage15"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU15">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	with Epinephrine
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have designed the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	device for a product containing epinephrine and have scaled up the commercial tooling and molds for this product.&nbsp;&nbsp;From a regulatory standpoint Teva filed this product as an ANDA, and the FDA accepted the filing as such.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently, Teva is conducting its own development work on the drug product (epinephrine).&nbsp;&nbsp;An amendment to the ANDA was filed with the FDA in December 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva received a complete response letter on February 23, 2016 relating to its epinephrine ANDA in which, according to Teva, the FDA identified certain major deficiencies. Teva is evaluating the CRL and intends to submit a response. Due to the major nature of the CRL, Teva expects that its epinephrine product will be substantially delayed from the previously anticipated launch date in the second half of 2016 and that any launch will not take place before 2017.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	with Sumatriptan
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have designed the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	device for a product containing sumatriptan and have scaled up the commercial tooling and molds for this product. In December 2015, the FDA approved our ANDA for 4 mg/0.5 mL and 6 mg/0.5 mL Sumatriptan Injection USP, indicated for adults for the acute treatment of migraine and cluster headache.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sumatriptan Injection USP represents the Company&#8217;s first ANDA approval of a complex generic and second product approved using the VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	auto injector platform.&nbsp;&nbsp;The VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	Sumatriptan product will be distributed under the terms of a license, supply and distribution arrangement with Teva, and is currently expected to be launched in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Disposable pen injector
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We previously provided clinical supplies for an undisclosed pen injector product to Teva.&nbsp;&nbsp;From a regulatory standpoint Teva has conducted a bioequivalence study for the product and determined the appropriate regulatory pathway is a 505(b)(2).&nbsp;&nbsp;The FDA has requested additional clinical work be conducted in support of the filing.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva decided to redesign the pen injector for this product and we completed the process of making significant design modifications.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva is developing this product for both Europe and the U.S. with the European clinical/regulatory team leading the development.&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2014, we completed device development and delivered devices for a drug stability program to support a regulatory filing.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Exenatide disposable pen injector
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have designed and produced pen injectors for the exenatide pen injector product.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva believes the regulatory pathway for this product is an ANDA pathway.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva initiated drug stability and completed the device development program and filed an ANDA with the FDA in the second half of 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;The ANDA was accepted by the FDA in October 2014 and is currently under FDA review.&nbsp;&nbsp;In December 2014, Amylin and AstraZeneca filed a complaint alleging patent infringement against Teva resulting in a thirty-month stay on FDA&#8217;s approval of the ANDA; the stay will expire in April 2017 unless the litigation is ended prior to that time.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The development timelines of the auto and pen injectors related to the Teva products are controlled by Teva.&nbsp;&nbsp;We expect development related to the Teva products to continue in 2015, but the timing and extent of near-term future development will be dependent on decisions made by Teva.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:4.54%;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QS with Makena
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	(hydroxyprogesterone caproate injection)
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are in the process of developing a variation of our VIBEX
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	QuickShot
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">

</SUP>
	auto injector for use with the progestin hormone drug
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
</FONT>
	Makena
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	under a license, development and supply agreement with AMAG. Under this arrangement, AMAG is responsible for the clinical development and preparation, and submission and maintenance of all regulatory applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are responsible for the design and development of the auto-injection device.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU16">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Manufacturing
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We use third parties to manufacture our products and product candidates and have agreements with those third parties to provide those services.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are responsible for device manufacturing and believe we are currently in compliance with current Quality System Regulations (&#8220;QSR&#8221;) established by the FDA and by the Medical Device Directive established by the European Commission. Injector and disposable parts are manufactured by third-party suppliers. Assembly and packaging of all of our products, including our needle-free device for all of our partners and OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	, is performed by third-party suppliers under our direction.&nbsp;&nbsp;Product release is performed by us.&nbsp;&nbsp;Below is a summary of our production, manufacturing, assembly and packaging arrangements with third parties:
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">

<TD VALIGN="TOP">

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Distribution
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In connection with the launch of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	we have contracted with a third-party logistics provider, Cardinal Health 105, Inc., also known as Specialty Pharmaceutical Services (&#8220;Cardinal&#8221;), for key services related to logistics, warehousing and inventory management, distribution, contract administration and chargeback processing, accounts receivable management and call center management. In addition, we will utilize third parties to perform various other services for us relating to sample accountability and regulatory monitoring, including adverse event reporting, safety database management and other product maintenance services.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Trade
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In connection with the launch of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	we have contracted with numerous wholesale distributors such as McKesson, Cardinal and Amerisource Bergen to distribute our OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	product to the retail pharmacies as well as the Veterans Administration and other governmental agencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to shipping our product, the major distributors will provide inventory and sales reports as well as other services.&nbsp;&nbsp;In exchange for these services we pay fees to certain distributors based on a percentage of wholesale acquisition cost.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Third Party Reimbursement and Pricing
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the U.S. and elsewhere, sales of pharmaceutical products depend in significant part on the availability of reimbursement to the consumer from third-party payors, such as government and private insurance plans. Third-party payors increasingly are challenging the prices charged for medical products and services and implementing other cost containment mechanisms. This is especially true in markets where generic options exist.&nbsp;&nbsp;It is, and will be, time consuming and expensive for us to go through the process of maintaining or seeking reimbursement to the consumer for our products from Medicaid, Medicare and private payors. Our products and those of our partners may not be considered cost effective, and coverage and reimbursement may not be available or sufficient to allow us to sell our products on a competitive and profitable basis, potentially resulting in contract changes with these major payors.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	14
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage17"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU17">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Third-party payers use tiered reimbursement which may adversely affect demand for OTREXUP
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	by placing it in a more expensive patient co-payment tier. We cannot be certain that OTREXUP
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	will successfully be placed on the li
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	st of drugs covered by particular health plan formularies. Additionally, with the introduction of another methotrexate/auto injector, third-party payers are currently demanding, and will most likely continue to demand more aggressive contractual terms from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Antares for favorable formulary placement for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	OTREXUP
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;Some states have also created preferred drug lists and include drugs on those lists only when the manufacturers agree to pay a supplemental rebate. If OTREXUP
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	is not included on these preferred dru
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	g lists, physicians may not be inclined to prescribe it to their Medicaid patients, thereby diminishing the potential market for OTREXUP
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	in this market segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our partnered products encounter the same issues with reimbursement stated above.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although we do not control the reimbursement rate or discounts contracted with third-party payers by our partners, it ultimately affects our royalty payments on products such as ZOMACTON
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, Elestrin
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	and Gelnique
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have encountered a widening gap between gross sales and net sales after discounts on both of these products which has negatively affected our royalty revenue.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Sales and Marketing
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have the worldwide marketing rights for OTREXUP&#8482; and commercialize OTREXUP&#8482; on our own in the U.S. We have an internal sales and marketing organization that includes approximately 50 employees directly involved in our commercialization and sales efforts.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2014, we had a contracted field force comprised of approximately 25 sales representatives to market the product in the U.S. to key rheumatology specialists. In December 2014, we terminated the contract with the contract sales organization, and in January 2015, we began to hire sales representatives to fill 32 territories.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have entered into agreements with vendors for commercialization services such as third-party contracting and distribution.&nbsp;&nbsp;We may enter into licensing and or additional distribution arrangements for commercialization of our products outside the U.S.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	For a discussion regarding revenues related to our products and services, as well as our revenues by geographic areas, see Results of Operations Revenues in Part II, Item 7 Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Note 10 to the Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	15
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage18"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:2PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The table above summarizes agreements under which our partners are selling products, conducting clinical evaluation, and performing development of our products. For competitive reasons, our partners may not divulge their name, the product name or the exact stage of clinical development.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In June 2000, we granted an exclusive license to BioSante (now ANI) to develop and commercialize our gel technology products for use in hormone replacement therapy in North America and other countries.&nbsp;&nbsp;ANI paid us an upfront payment upon execution of the agreement and is also required to make royalty payments to us on commercial sales of the products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently we expect that Elestrin
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, which is sublicensed by Meda, will be the only product commercialized under this license agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In January 2003, we entered into a revised License Agreement with Ferring, under which we licensed certain of our intellectual property and extended the territories available to Ferring for use of certain of our reusable needle-free injection devices to include all countries and territories in the world except Asia/Pacific. Specifically, we granted to Ferring an exclusive, royalty-bearing license, within a prescribed manufacturing territory, to utilize certain of our reusable needle-free injector devices for the field of hGH until the expiration of the last to expire of the patents in any country in the territory. We granted to Ferring similar non-exclusive rights outside of the prescribed manufacturing territory.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2007, we amended this agreement providing for non-exclusive rights in Asia along with other changes to financial terms of the agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;We receive a purchase price and a royalty for each device sold to Ferring and a royalty on their hGH sales if we meet certain product quality metrics.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have an agreement with JCR through 2016 under which they will continue to market our needle free injector in Japan for use with their hGH product Growject
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;We receive a negotiated purchase price for each device sold, as well as royalties on JCR&#8217;s net sales of hGH. We have the option to renew the agreement in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In July 2006, we entered into an exclusive License Development and Supply Agreement with Teva. Pursuant to the agreement, Teva is obligated to purchase all of its delivery device requirements from us for an epinephrine auto injector product to be marketed in the U.S. and Canada. We received an upfront cash payment and will receive a negotiated purchase price for each device sold, as well as royalties on sales of their product.&nbsp;&nbsp;This agreement has been amended numerous times and provides for payment of capital equipment and other development work that was outside the scope of the original agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The agreement will continue until the later of July 2016 or the expiration of the last to expire patent that is filed no later than 12 months after FDA approval.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have multiple patents that have been granted by the USPTO which cover this product and expire in 2031.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have and plan to continue to file patent applications covering this product.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September 2006, we entered into a Supply Agreement with Teva.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to the agreement, Teva is obligated to purchase all of its delivery device requirements from us for hGH marketed in the U.S. We received an upfront cash payment and have received milestone fees and royalty payments on Teva&#8217;s net sales of hGH, as well as a purchase price for each device sold.&nbsp;&nbsp;The original term of this agreement extended through September 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;In May 2013, the agreement was amended to provide for one-year automatic renewals unless terminated by either party six months ahead of the expiring term.&nbsp;&nbsp;In December 2014, Ferring acquired the U.S. rights from Teva and assumed Teva&#8217;s obligations under the Supply Agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In December 2007, we entered into a license, development and supply agreement with Teva under which we will develop and supply a disposable pen injector for use with exenatide and an undisclosed patient-administered pharmaceutical product.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the agreement, an upfront payment, development milestones, and royalties on product sales are to be received by us under certain circumstances.&nbsp;&nbsp;In January 2011, this agreement was amended to provide payments to us for capital equipment and other development work.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2015, 2014, and 2013, statements of work in connection with continued development of these two products were agreed upon, providing additional payments to us.&nbsp;&nbsp;This agreement will continue until the later of December 2017 or the expiration date of the last to expire patent covering the device or product that is filed no later than 12 months after FDA approval, and will be automatically renewed for successive periods of two years each.&nbsp;&nbsp;Currently the expiration date of the last to expire patent is 2029, and we have filed patent applications that, if granted, would expire in 2034 and 2035.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2009, we entered into a license agreement with Ferring under which we licensed certain of our patents and agreed to transfer know-how for our transdermal gel technology for certain pharmaceutical products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under this agreement, we received an upfront payment, milestone payments and will receive additional milestone payments as certain defined product development milestones are achieved.&nbsp;&nbsp;The agreement is effective until the last to expire patent.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In July 2011, we entered into a licensing agreement with Actavis, formerly Watson, under which Actavis will commercialize our oxybutynin gel 3% product in the U.S. and Canada.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under this agreement we received payments for certain manufacturing start-up activities, delivery of launch quantities, and royalties on both our oxybutynin gel 3% product and their oxybutynin gel product Gelnique
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	10%, and will potentially receive sales based milestone payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;The term of the agreement ends on the later of April 2024 or the expiration date of the last to expire patent.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	16
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage19"></A>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU18">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In December 2011, we entered into a licensing agreement with Pfizer Consumer Healthcare (&#8220;Pfizer&#8221;) for one of our drug delivery technologies to develop an undis
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	closed product on an exclusive basis for North America.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 5, 2015, we received a written notice of termination of the Agreement from Pfizer.&nbsp;&nbsp;Accordingly, the Agreement terminated on November 5, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2012, we entered into a license, supply and distribution agreement with Teva for an auto injector product containing sumatriptan for the treatment of migraines.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will manufacture the device and do final assembly and packaging of the final product, and Teva will manufacture and supply the drug and will commercialize and distribute the product in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;Teva also received an option for rights in other territories.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the agreement, we received an upfront payment and will receive a milestone payment upon commercial launch.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, net profits will be split 50/50 between us and Teva.&nbsp;&nbsp;The term of the agreement is seven years from commercial launch, with automatic one-year renewals unless terminated by either party after the initial term.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In November 2013, we entered into a promotion and license agreement with LEO Pharma.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under this agreement we granted LEO Pharma the exclusive right to promote OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	to dermatologists for symptomatic control of severe recalcitrant psoriasis in adults in the U.S.&nbsp;&nbsp;LEO Pharma is responsible for promotion and marketing activities in dermatology and we are responsible for the supply of OTREXUP
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	product and samples.&nbsp;&nbsp;We received from LEO Pharma a non-refundable upfront payment of $5.0 million and received a second milestone payment of $5.0 million upon launch of the product and meeting other performance obligations in March 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The agreement was terminated in June 2015 and we regained the exclusive U.S. marketing rights to OTREXUP&#8482;.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In September 2014, we entered into a development and license agreement with Lumara Health, Inc., which was subsequently acquired by AMAG, to develop and supply an auto injector system for use with a progestin drug (hydroxyprogesterone caproate)
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	indicated for the prevention of pre-term labor in pregnant women.
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	Under the agreement, we granted an exclusive, worldwide, royalty-bearing license, with the right to sublicense, to certain intellectual property rights, including know-how, patents and trademarks, and received an upfront payment for our license and development activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are also entitled to milestone payments upon the achievement of pre-determined amount of net sales of the product.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	AMAG is responsible for the clinical development and preparation, submission and maintenance of all regulatory applications, to manufacture and supply the drug to be used in the product, and to market, distribute and sell the product.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are the exclusive supplier of the auto-injection system devices for the product and are responsible for the manufacture and supply of the devices and final assembly and packaging of the finished product.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the arrangement, we will receive payment for each device, and royalties based on the net sales of products commencing on product launch in a particular country until the product is no longer developed, marketed, sold or offered for sale in such country. The royalty rates range from high single digit to low double digits and are tiered based on levels of net sales of products and decrease after the expiration of licensed patents or where there are generic equivalents to the auto injector product being sold in a particular country.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:18PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Competition
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:6PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Competition in the methotrexate market includes tablets and parenteral forms that are currently marketed in the U.S. by several generic manufacturers, including Teva, Mylan, Roxane, Bedford Labs, APP Pharmaceuticals, and Hospira and Accord Healthcare.&nbsp;&nbsp;In several European countries, Canada, and South Korea, Medac International or its licensees market methotrexate in prefilled syringes (Metoject
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	) and in 2013 launched an auto injector with methotrexate in those territories.&nbsp;&nbsp;On July 14, 2014, Medac Pharma, a privately held pharmaceutical company, announced FDA approval of an NDA for their product candidate, Rasuvo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	, a subcutaneous injectable methotrexate in a ready-to-use injection device for use in the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis, poly-articular course juvenile arthritis and psoriasis.&nbsp;&nbsp;The product was subsequently launched on October 6, 2014 and is available in 10 dosage strengths, ranging from 7.5 mg to 30 mg in 2.5 mg increments.&nbsp;&nbsp;Other commonly used pharmaceutical treatments for rheumatoid arthritis include analgesics, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), corticosteroids, so-called disease modifying anti-rheumatic drugs (DMARDs) and biologic response modifiers.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to methotrexate, the DMARDs include azathioprine (Imuran
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), cyclosporine (Neoral
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), hydroxychloroquine (Plaquenil
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), auranofin (Ridura
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), leflunomide (Arava
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	) and sulfasalazine (Azulfidine
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	).&nbsp;&nbsp;The biologic response modifiers include etanercept (Enbrel
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), adalimumab (Humira
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), golimumab (Simponi
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), tocilizumab (Actemra
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), certolizumab (Cimzia
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), infliximab (Remicaid
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), abatacept (Orencia
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	), and rituximab (Rituxan
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	). They are often prescribed in combination with DMARDs such as methotrexate.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:4.54%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="ATRS-10K_20151231_HTM__AEIOULASTRENDEREDPAGEBREAKAEIOU19">
</A>
	Competition in the U.S. testosterone replacement market includes Abbvie&#8217;s Androgel
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	and Androgel
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	1.62%,&nbsp;&nbsp;Lilly&#8217;s Axiron
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, Endo Pharmaceuticals&#8217; Fortesta
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	,&nbsp;&nbsp;Delatestryl
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, Testim
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	(and the authorized generic), Striant
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	and Testopel
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, Pfizer&#8217;s Depo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	-Testosterone, Actavis&#8217; Androderm
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, Upsher-Smith&#8217;s Vogelxo
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
</SUP>
	and several generic testosterone in oil products sold by Actavis, Sandoz, Mylan, Bedford Labs, Teva and others.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, at least three additional oral treatments for low testosterone levels are either in development or under active review at the FDA. Clarus Therapeutics is developing an oral formulation of testosterone undecanoate, Rextoro
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#8482;
</SUP>
	and Lipocine is also developing an oral formulation of testosterone undecanoate.&nbsp;&nbsp;Repros Therapeutics, Inc. submitted an NDA to the FDA on February 2, 2015 for Androxal
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	&#174;
</SUP>
	, a single isomer of clomiphene citrate under development for the treatment of secondary hypogonadism in overweight men wishing to restore normal testicular function, and received a complete response letter in November 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2014, Endo Pharmaceuticals received U.S. FDA approval of testosterone undecanoate injection,
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
